In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle event mappings** on `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when activity is pausing
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when activity is no longer visible
            }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app =>
            {
                // Runs when the iOS app enters background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the single entry point for all platform lifecycle hooks.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code compilation-safe.
- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- Each callback receives the platform-native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call platform APIs directly.
